# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: avalonia-ui
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Within computing, **cross-platform software** (also called **multi-platform software**, **platform-agnostic software**, or **platform-independent software**) is computer software that is designed to work in several computing platforms.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] For example, a cross-platform application may run on Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform software may run on many platforms, or as few as two.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Some frameworks for cross-platform development are Codename One, ArkUI-X, Kivy, Qt, GTK, Flutter, NativeScript, Xamarin, Apache Cordova, Ionic, and React Native.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] A hardware platform can refer to an instruction set architecture.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] For example: ARM or the x86 architecture.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] These machines can run different operating systems.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Smartphones and tablets generally run ARM architecture, these often run Android or iOS and other mobile operating systems.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] A software platform can be either an operating system (OS) or programming environment, though more commonly it is a combination of both.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] An exception is Java, which uses an OS-independent virtual machine (VM) to execute Java bytecode.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] The Java language is typically compiled to run on a VM that is part of the Java platform.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] The Java virtual machine (Java VM, JVM) is a CPU implemented in software, which runs all Java code.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] This enables the same code to run on all systems that implement a JVM.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Java software can be executed by a hardware-based Java processor.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] This is used mostly in embedded systems.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Java code running in the JVM has access to OS-related services, like disk input/output (I/O) and network access, if the appropriate privileges are granted.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] The JVM makes the system calls on behalf of the Java application.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] This lets users to decide the appropriate protection level, depending on an access-control list (ACL).
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] For example, disk and network access is usually enabled for desktop applications, but not for browser-based applets.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] The Java Native Interface (JNI) can also be used to access OS-specific functions, with a loss of portability.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Currently, Java Standard Edition software can run on Microsoft Windows, macOS, several Unix-like OSs, and several real-time operating systems for embedded devices.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] For mobile applications, browser plugins are used for Windows and Mac based devices, and Android has built-in support for Java.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] There are also subsets of Java, such as Java Card or Java Platform, Micro Edition, designed for resource-constrained devices.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] For software to be considered cross-platform, it must function on more than one computer architecture or OS.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Developing such software can be a time-consuming task because different OSs have different application programming interfaces (API).
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Software written for one OS may not automatically work on all architectures that OS supports.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Just because software is written in a popular programming language such as C or C++, it does not mean it will run on all OSs that support that language—or even on different versions of the same OS.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Web applications are typically described as cross-platform because, ideally, they are accessible from any web browser: the browser is the platform.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Web applications generally employ a client–server model, but vary widely in complexity and functionality.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] It can be hard to reconcile the desire for features with the need for compatibility.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Basic web applications perform all or most processing from a stateless server, and pass the result to the client web browser.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] All user interaction with the application consists of simple exchanges of data requests and server responses.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] This type of application was the norm in the early phases of World Wide Web application development.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Such applications follow a simple transaction model, identical to that of serving static web pages.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Today, they are still relatively common, especially where cross-platform compatibility and simplicity are deemed more critical than advanced functionality.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Prominent examples of advanced web applications include the Web interface to Gmail and Google Maps.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Such applications routinely depend on additional features found only in the more recent versions of popular web browsers.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] These features include Ajax, JavaScript, Dynamic HTML, SVG, and other components of rich web applications.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Because of the competing interests of compatibility and functionality, numerous design strategies have emerged.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Many software systems use a layered architecture where platform-dependent code is restricted to the upper- and lowermost layers.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Graceful degradation attempts to provide the same or similar functionality to all users and platforms, while diminishing that functionality to a least common denominator for more limited client browsers.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] For example, a user attempting to use a limited-feature browser to access Gmail may notice that Gmail switches to basic mode, with reduced functionality but still of use.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Some software is maintained in distinct codebases for different (hardware and OS) platforms, with equivalent functionality.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] This requires more effort to maintain the code, but can be worthwhile where the amount of platform-specific code is high.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] This strategy relies on having one codebase that may be compiled to multiple platform-specific formats.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] One technique is conditional compilation.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] With this technique, code that is common to all platforms is not repeated.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Blocks of code that are only relevant to certain platforms are made conditional, so that they are only interpreted or compiled when needed.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Another technique is separation of functionality, which disables functionality not supported by browsers or OSs, while still delivering a complete application to the user.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] (See also: Separation of concerns.) This technique is used in web development where interpreted code (as in scripting languages) can query the platform it is running on to execute different blocks conditionally.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Third-party libraries attempt to simplify cross-platform capability by hiding the complexities of client differentiation behind a single, unified API, at the expense of vendor lock-in.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Responsive web design (RWD) is a Web design approach aimed at crafting the visual layout of sites to provide an optimal viewing experience—easy reading and navigation with a minimum of resizing, panning, and scrolling—across a wide range of devices, from mobile phones to desktop computer monitors.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Little or no platform-specific code is used with this technique.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform applications need much more integration testing.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Some web browsers prohibit installation of different versions on the same machine.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] There are several approaches used to target multiple platforms, but all of them result in software that requires substantial manual effort for testing and maintenance.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Techniques such as full virtualization are sometimes used as a workaround for this problem.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Tools such as the Page Object Model allow cross-platform tests to be scripted so that one test case covers multiple versions of an app.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] If different versions have similar user interfaces, all can be tested with one test case.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Web applications are becoming increasingly popular but many computer users still use traditional application software which does not rely on a client/web-server architecture.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] The distinction between traditional and web applications is not always clear.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Features, installation methods and architectures for web and traditional applications overlap and blur the distinction.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Nevertheless, this simplifying distinction is a common and useful generalization.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Traditional application software has been distributed as binary files, especially executable files.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Executables only support the platform they were built for—which means that a single cross-platform executable could be very bloated with code that never executes on a particular platform.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Instead, generally there is a selection of executables, each built for one platform.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] For software that is distributed as a binary executable, such as that written in C or C++, there must be a software build for each platform, using a toolset that translates—transcompiles—a single codebase into multiple binary executables.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] For example, Firefox, an open-source web browser, is available on Windows, macOS (both PowerPC and x86 through what Apple Inc. calls a Universal binary), Linux, and BSD on multiple computer architectures.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] The four platforms (in this case, Windows, macOS, Linux, and BSD) are separate executable distributions, although they come largely from the same source code.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] In rare cases, executable code built for several platforms is combined into a single executable file called a fat binary.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] The use of different toolsets may not be enough to build a working executables for different platforms.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] In this case, programmers must *port* the source code to the new platform.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] For example, an application such as Firefox, which already runs on Windows on the x86 family, can be modified and re-built to run on Linux on the x86 (and potentially other architectures) as well.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] The multiple versions of the code may be stored as separate codebases, or merged into one codebase.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] An alternative to porting is *cross-platform virtualization*, where applications compiled for one platform can run on another without modification of the source code or binaries.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] As an example, Apple's Rosetta, which is built into Intel-based Macintosh computers, runs applications compiled for the previous generation of Macs that used PowerPC CPUs.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Another example is IBM PowerVM Lx86, which allows Linux/x86 applications to run unmodified on the Linux/Power OS.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] A script can be considered to be cross-platform if its interpreter is available on multiple platforms and the script only uses the facilities built into the language.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] For example, a script written in Python for a Unix-like system will likely run with little or no modification on Windows, because Python also runs on Windows; indeed there are many implementations (e.g.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] The same goes for many of the open-source scripting languages.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Unlike binary executable files, the same script can be used on all computers that have software to interpret the script.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] This is because the script is generally stored in plain text in a text file.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] There may be some trivial issues, such as the representation of a new line character.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform or multi-platform is a term that can also apply to video games released on a range of video game consoles.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Examples of cross-platform games include: *Miner 2049er*, *Tomb Raider: Legend*, *FIFA series*, *NHL series* and *Minecraft*.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Each has been released across a variety of gaming platforms, such as the Wii, PlayStation 3, Xbox 360, personal computers, and mobile devices.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Some platforms are harder to write for than others, requiring more time to develop the video game to the same standard.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] To offset this, a video game may be released on a few platforms first, then later on others.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Typically, this happens when a new gaming system is released, because video game developers need to acquaint themselves with its hardware and software.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Some games may not be cross-platform because of licensing agreements between developers and video game console manufacturers that limit development to one particular console.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] As an example, Disney could create a game with the intention of release on the latest Nintendo and Sony game consoles.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Should Disney license the game with Sony first, it may be required to release the game solely on Sony's console for a short time or indefinitely.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Several developers have implemented ways to play games online while using different platforms.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Psyonix, Epic Games, Microsoft, and Valve all possess technology that allows Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 gamers to play with PC gamers, leaving the decision of which platform to use to consumers.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] The first game to allow this level of interactivity between PC and console games (Dreamcast with specially produced keyboard and mouse) was *Quake 3*.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Games that feature cross-platform online play include *Rocket League*, *Final Fantasy XIV*, *Street Fighter V*, *Killer Instinct*, *Paragon* and *Fable Fortune,* and *Minecraft* with its Better Together update on Windows 10, VR editions, Pocket Edition and Xbox One.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform programming is the practice of deliberately writing software to work on more than one platform.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] There are different ways to write a cross-platform application.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] One approach is to create multiple versions of the same software in different *source trees*—in other words, the Microsoft Windows version of an application might have one set of source code files and the Macintosh version another, while a FOSS *nix system might have a third.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] While this is straightforward, compared to developing for only one platform it can cost much more to pay a larger team or release products more slowly.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] It can also result in more bugs to be tracked and fixed.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Another approach is to use software that hides the differences between the platforms.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] This abstraction layer insulates the application from the platform.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Such applications are *platform agnostic*.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Applications that run on the JVM are built this way.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Some applications mix various methods of cross-platform programming to create the final application.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] An example is the Firefox web browser, which uses abstraction to build some of the lower-level components, with separate source subtrees for implementing platform-specific features (like the GUI), and the implementation of more than one scripting language to ease software portability.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Firefox implements XUL, CSS and JavaScript for extending the browser, in addition to classic Netscape-style browser plugins.
[src:avalonia-ui/cross-platform-software] Much of the browser itself is written in XUL, CSS, and JavaScript.
[src:avalonia-ui/data-binding] In computer programming, **data-binding** is a general technique that binds data sources from the provider and consumer together and synchronizes them.
[src:avalonia-ui/data-binding] This is usually done with two data/information sources with different languages, as in XML data binding and UI data binding.
[src:avalonia-ui/data-binding] In UI data binding, data and information objects of the same language, but different logic function are bound together (e.g., Java UI elements to Java objects).
[src:avalonia-ui/data-binding] In a data binding process, each data change is reflected automatically by the elements that are bound to the data.
[src:avalonia-ui/data-binding] The term data binding is also used in cases where an outer representation of data in an element changes, and the underlying data is automatically updated to reflect this change.
[src:avalonia-ui/data-binding] As an example, a change in a `TextBox` element could modify the underlying data value.
[src:avalonia-ui/extensible-application-markup-language] XAML is used extensively in Windows Presentation Foundation (WPF), Silverlight, Workflow Foundation (WF), Windows UI Library (WinUI), Universal Windows Platform (UWP), and .NET Multi-platform App UI (.NET MAUI).
[src:avalonia-ui/extensible-application-markup-language] In WPF and UWP, XAML is a user interface markup language to define UI elements, data binding, and events.
[src:avalonia-ui/extensible-application-markup-language] XAML elements map directly to Common Language Runtime (CLR) object instances, while XAML attributes map to CLR properties and events on those objects.
[src:avalonia-ui/extensible-application-markup-language] Anything that is created or implemented in XAML can be expressed using a more traditional .NET language, such as C# or Visual Basic .NET.
[src:avalonia-ui/extensible-application-markup-language] However, a key aspect of the technology is the reduced complexity needed for tools to process XAML, because it is based on XML.
[src:avalonia-ui/extensible-application-markup-language] XAML originally stood for Extensible Avalon Markup Language, *Avalon* being the code-name for Windows Presentation Foundation (WPF).
[src:avalonia-ui/extensible-application-markup-language] Before the end of .NET Framework 3.0 development, however, Microsoft adopted XAML for Workflow Foundation (WF).
[src:avalonia-ui/extensible-application-markup-language] In WPF, XAML describes visual user interfaces.
[src:avalonia-ui/extensible-application-markup-language] WPF allows for the definition of both 2D and 3D objects, rotations, animations, and a variety of other effects and features.
[src:avalonia-ui/extensible-application-markup-language] A XAML file can be compiled into a Binary Application Markup Language (BAML) file, which may be inserted as a resource into a .NET Framework assembly.
[src:avalonia-ui/extensible-application-markup-language] At run-time, the framework engine extracts the BAML file from assembly resources, parses it, and creates a corresponding WPF visual tree or workflow.
[src:avalonia-ui/extensible-application-markup-language] In WF contexts, XAML describes potentially long-running declarative logic, such as those created by process modeling tools and rules systems.
[src:avalonia-ui/extensible-application-markup-language] The serialization format for workflows was previously called XOML, to differentiate it from UI markup use of XAML, but now they are no longer distinguished.
[src:avalonia-ui/extensible-application-markup-language] However, the file extension for files containing the workflow markup is still ".xoml".
[src:avalonia-ui/extensible-application-markup-language] XAML uses a specific way to define look and feel called *Template*s; differing from Cascading Style Sheet syntax, it is closer to XBL.
[src:avalonia-ui/extensible-application-markup-language] To create XAML files, one could use Microsoft Expression Blend, Microsoft Visual Studio, the hostable WF visual designer, or XAMLPad.
[src:avalonia-ui/extensible-application-markup-language] This Windows Presentation Foundation example shows the text "Hello, world!" in the top-level XAML container called Canvas.
[src:avalonia-ui/extensible-application-markup-language] The schema (the `xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/..."` part) may have to be changed to work on some computers.
[src:avalonia-ui/extensible-application-markup-language] A crucial part of utilizing XAML to its full potential is making appropriate usage of binding, as well as creating custom user elements as required.
[src:avalonia-ui/extensible-application-markup-language] These versions have some differences in the parsing behavior.
[src:avalonia-ui/extensible-application-markup-language] Additionally, the Silverlight 4 XAML parser is not 100% backward-compatible with Silverlight 3 files.
[src:avalonia-ui/extensible-application-markup-language] Silverlight 3 XAML files may be rejected or parsed differently by the Silverlight 4 parser.
[src:avalonia-ui/extensible-application-markup-language] Besides Microsoft implementations, there is also OpenSilver (formerly known as CSHTML5), a contemporary web technology implementation.
[src:avalonia-ui/extensible-application-markup-language] Historically, XAML based applications could be run in some web browsers, such as Internet Explorer and Firefox.
[src:avalonia-ui/extensible-application-markup-language] This could be achieved through XBAP files created from WPF applications, or via the Silverlight browser plugin.
[src:avalonia-ui/extensible-application-markup-language] However, both these methods are now unsupported on all major browsers due to their reliance on the discontinued NPAPI browser plugin interface.
[src:avalonia-ui/extensible-application-markup-language] In 2007, European Committee for Interoperable Systems (ECIS) – a coalition of mostly American software companies – accused Microsoft of attempting to hijack HTML and replace it with XAML, thus creating a vendor lock-in.
[src:avalonia-ui/extensible-application-markup-language] Jeremy Reimer, writing for *Ars Technica* described this comment as "the most egregious error" and added that XAML is unlikely to ever replace HTML.
[src:avalonia-ui/model-view-viewmodel] The *viewmodel* of MVVM is a value converter, meaning it is responsible for exposing (converting) the data objects from the model in such a way they can be easily managed and presented.
[src:avalonia-ui/model-view-viewmodel] In this respect, the viewmodel is more *model* than *view*, and handles most (if not all) of the view's display logic.
[src:avalonia-ui/model-view-viewmodel] The viewmodel may implement a mediator pattern, organizing access to the back-end logic around the set of use cases supported by the view.
[src:avalonia-ui/model-view-viewmodel] MVVM is a variation of Martin Fowler's Presentation Model design pattern.
[src:avalonia-ui/model-view-viewmodel] MVVM is very similar to the Model-view-presenter pattern.
[src:avalonia-ui/model-view-viewmodel] It was invented by Microsoft architects Ken Cooper and Ted Peters specifically to simplify event-driven programming of user interfaces.
[src:avalonia-ui/model-view-viewmodel] The pattern was incorporated into the Windows Presentation Foundation (WPF) (Microsoft's .NET graphics system) and Silverlight, WPF's Internet application derivative.
[src:avalonia-ui/model-view-viewmodel] John Gossman, a Microsoft WPF and Silverlight architect, announced MVVM on his blog in 2005.
[src:avalonia-ui/model-view-viewmodel] Model–view–viewmodel is also referred to as **model–view–binder**, especially in implementations not involving the .NET platform.
[src:avalonia-ui/model-view-viewmodel] ZK, a web application framework written in Java, and the JavaScript library KnockoutJS use model–view–binder.
[src:avalonia-ui/model-view-viewmodel] , which represents content (a data-centric approach).
[src:avalonia-ui/model-view-viewmodel] is the structure, layout, and appearance of what a user sees on the screen.
[src:avalonia-ui/model-view-viewmodel] (properties, event callbacks, etc.) that is defined to link the view and view model.
[src:avalonia-ui/model-view-viewmodel] is an abstraction of the view exposing public properties and commands.
[src:avalonia-ui/model-view-viewmodel] , which automates communication between the view and its bound properties in the view model.
[src:avalonia-ui/model-view-viewmodel] The view model has been described as a state of the data in the model.
[src:avalonia-ui/model-view-viewmodel] The main difference between the view model and the Presenter in the MVP pattern is that the presenter has a reference to a view, whereas the view model does not.
[src:avalonia-ui/model-view-viewmodel] Instead, a view directly binds to properties on the view model to send and receive updates.
[src:avalonia-ui/model-view-viewmodel] Declarative data and command-binding are implicit in the MVVM pattern.
[src:avalonia-ui/model-view-viewmodel] The binder frees the developer from being obliged to write boiler-plate logic to synchronize the view model and view.
[src:avalonia-ui/model-view-viewmodel] and without a binder, one would typically use MVP or MVC instead and have to write more boilerplate (or generate it with some other tool).
[src:avalonia-ui/model-view-viewmodel] MVVM was designed to remove virtually all GUI code ("code-behind") from the view layer, by using data binding functions in WPF (Windows Presentation Foundation) to better facilitate the separation of view layer development from the rest of the pattern.
[src:avalonia-ui/model-view-viewmodel] Instead of requiring user experience (UX) developers to write GUI code, they can use the framework markup language (e.g.
[src:avalonia-ui/model-view-viewmodel] XAML) and create data bindings to the view model, which is written and maintained by application developers.
[src:avalonia-ui/model-view-viewmodel] The separation of roles allows interactive designers to focus on UX needs rather than programming of business logic.
[src:avalonia-ui/model-view-viewmodel] The layers of an application can thus be developed in multiple work streams for higher productivity.
[src:avalonia-ui/model-view-viewmodel] Even when a single developer works on the entire codebase, a proper separation of the view from the model is more productive, as the user interface typically changes frequently and late in the development cycle based on end-user feedback.
[src:avalonia-ui/model-view-viewmodel] The MVVM pattern attempts to gain both advantages of separation of functional development provided by MVC, while leveraging the advantages of data bindings and the framework by binding data as close to the pure application model as possible.
[src:avalonia-ui/model-view-viewmodel] It uses the binder, view model, and any business layers' data-checking features to validate incoming data.
[src:avalonia-ui/model-view-viewmodel] The result is that the model and framework drive as much of the operations as possible, eliminating or minimizing application logic which directly manipulates the view (e.g., code-behind).
[src:avalonia-ui/model-view-viewmodel] John Gossman has criticized the MVVM pattern and its application in specific uses, stating that MVVM can be "overkill" when creating simple user interfaces.
[src:avalonia-ui/model-view-viewmodel] For larger applications, he believes that generalizing the viewmodel upfront can be difficult, and that large-scale data binding can lead to lower performance.
[src:avalonia-ui/model-view-viewmodel] The following are simple examples of an implementation of the MVVM pattern.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] The **.NET** platform (pronounced as "*dot net"*; formerly named **.NET Core**) is a free and open-source, managed computer software framework for Windows, Linux, and macOS operating systems.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] It is a cross-platform successor to the .NET Framework.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] The project is mainly developed by Microsoft employees by way of the .NET Foundation and is today released under an MIT License.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] New versions of the .NET platform are released annually, typically in November.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] The most recent version of .NET is .NET 10, released in November 2025, which is a long-term support (LTS) version, and is scheduled to receive updates until November 2028.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] In the late 1990s, Microsoft began developing a managed code runtime and programming language (C#) which it billed together as part of the ".NET platform", with the core runtime and software libraries comprising the .NET Framework.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] Soon after the announcement of the C# language at the Professional Developers Conference in 2000 and previews of its software became available, Microsoft began a standardization effort through ECMA for what it dubbed the Common Language Infrastructure.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] The company continued development and support of its own implementation as proprietary, closed source software in the meantime.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] Miguel de Icaza describes .NET Core as a "redesigned version of .NET that is based on the simplified version of the class libraries", and Microsoft's Immo Landwerth explained that .NET Core would be "the foundation of all future .NET platforms".
[src:avalonia-ui/net] At the time of the announcement, the initial release of the .NET Core project had been seeded with a subset of the libraries' source code and coincided with the relicensing of Microsoft's existing .NET reference source away from the restrictions of the Ms-RSL.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] Landwerth acknowledged the disadvantages of the formerly selected shared license, explaining that it made codename Rotor "a non-starter" as a community-developed open source project because it did not meet the criteria of an Open Source Initiative (OSI) approved license.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] .NET Core 1.0 was released on June 27, 2016, along with Microsoft Visual Studio 2015 Update 3, which enables .NET Core development. .NET Core 1.0.4 and .NET Core 1.1.1 were released along with .NET Core Tools 1.0 and Visual Studio 2017 on March 7, 2017.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] .NET Core 2.0 was released on August 14, 2017, along with Visual Studio 2017 15.3, ASP.NET Core 2.0, and Entity Framework Core 2.0. .NET Core 2.1 was released on May 30, 2018.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] NET Core 2.2 was released on December 4, 2018.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] .NET Core 3 was released on September 23, 2019.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] NET Core 3 adds support for Windows desktop application development and significant performance improvements throughout the base library.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] In November 2020, Microsoft released .NET 5.0.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] The "Core" branding was abandoned and version 4.0 was skipped to avoid conflation with .NET Framework, of which the latest releases had all used 4.x versioning for all significant (non-bugfix) releases since 2010.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] .NET Core Runtime roughly uses semantic versioning, the *major.minor.patch* format.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] Major versions are incremented with "significant changes", API-breaking changes, or with the major version increase in an existing dependency.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] Minor versions are incremented with the addition of API features, dependencies, or with the minor version increase in an existing dependency.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] Patch versions are given for bug fixes, new platform support, or other changes not included above.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] As of 2019, runtime versions are backwards-compatible within the same major version number.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] For example, .NET Core 2.2 is able to run programs built for .NET Core 2.1.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] Runtime versions in the same minor version.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] This appears to have relaxed since .NET 5.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] A "roll-forward" behavior allows any .NET program to be run on any newer version given the correct settings.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] The SDK does not use semantic versioning.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] As of 2019, it supports targeting *every* runtime version prior to its maximum supported version.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] As of 2020, this extends down to .NET Framework runtimes as well, though downloading an additional "targeting pack" from NuGet may be necessary.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] The major and minor versions of an SDK always matches the major and minor versions of the runtime it contains or is aligned for.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] Alpine Linux, which primarily supports and uses musl libc, is supported since .NET Core 2.1.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] Windows Arm64 is natively supported since .NET 5.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] Previously, .NET on ARM meant applications compiled for the x86 architecture and run through the ARM emulation layer.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] Linux .NET runs on Power ISA to some extent since .NET 7, officially no support is claimed by Microsoft but .NET does contain code for Power ISA compatibility for Linux systems and is able to be compiled for Power ISA systems specifically 64 bit Little Endian variant.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] .NET fully supports C# and F# (and C++/CLI as of 3.1; only enabled on Windows) and supports Visual Basic .NET (for version 15.5 in .NET Core 5.0.100-preview.4, and some old versions supported in old .NET Core).
[src:avalonia-ui/net] VB.NET compiles and runs on .NET, but as of .NET Core 3.1, the separate Visual Basic Runtime is not implemented.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] Microsoft initially announced that .NET Core 3 would include the Visual Basic Runtime, but after two years the timeline for such support was updated to .NET 5.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] .NET supports the following cross-platform scenarios: ASP.NET Core web apps, command-line/console apps, libraries and Universal Windows Platform apps.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] Prior to .NET Core 3.0, it did not implement Windows Forms or Windows Presentation Foundation (WPF), which render the standard GUI for desktop software on Windows.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] However, from .NET Core 3 on, it started implementing them along with Universal Windows Platform (UWP).
[src:avalonia-ui/net] It was also possible to write cross-platform graphical applications using .NET with the GTK# language-binding for the GTK widget toolkit, but this binding has not been maintained for many years.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] Unlike .NET Framework, which is serviced using Windows Update, .NET used to rely on its package manager to receive updates.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] Since December 2020, however, .NET updates started being delivered via Windows Update as well.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] NuGet serves as the primary distribution mechanism for libraries and tools in the .NET ecosystem, including third-party components that extend core functionality.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] Among these are ADO.NET-compatible data providers, which offer database connectivity for systems beyond the default SQL Server support.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] These providers enable direct access to databases such as Oracle, MySQL, PostgreSQL, and others, and are commonly used in applications that require cross-platform data access, integration with ORM technologies, or support for specific database features.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] The two main components of .NET are CoreCLR and CoreFX, which are comparable to the Common Language Runtime (CLR) and the Framework Class Library (FCL) of the .NET Framework's Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) implementation.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] As an implementation of CLI's Standard Libraries, CoreFX shares a subset of .NET Framework APIs, however, it also comes with its own APIs that are not part of the .NET Framework.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] A variant of the .NET library is used for UWP.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] The .NET command-line interface offers an execution entry point for operating systems and provides developer services like compilation and package management.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] The official community mascot of .NET is the .NET Bot (stylized as "dotnet bot" or "dotnet-bot").
[src:avalonia-ui/net] The dotnet bot served as the placeholder developer for the initial check-in of the .NET source code when it was open-sourced.
[src:avalonia-ui/net] It has since been used as the official mascot.
[src:avalonia-ui/skia-graphics-engine] The **Skia Graphics Engine** or **Skia** is an open-source 2D graphics library written in C++.
[src:avalonia-ui/skia-graphics-engine] Skia abstracts away platform-specific graphics APIs (which differ from one to another).
[src:avalonia-ui/skia-graphics-engine] Skia Inc. originally developed the library; Google acquired it in 2005, and then released the software as open source licensed under the New BSD free software license in 2008.
[src:avalonia-ui/skia-graphics-engine] In order to stay multi-platform, Skia supports several (platform-dependent) back-ends.
[src:avalonia-ui/skia-graphics-engine] Skia is most similar in purpose to Cairo or Pathfinder (meaning that it focuses on drawing) rather than to other more elaborate APIs like that of Qt that provide their own widgets and UI description language etc.
[src:avalonia-ui/skia-graphics-engine] The library is used as of 2023 in Google Chrome, ChromeOS, ChromiumOS, Mozilla Firefox, Mozilla Thunderbird, Android, Firefox OS, Flutter, Ladybird, Avalonia (from Alpha 4), LibreOffice (from version 7.0) and RAD Studio(since version 12.0).
[src:avalonia-ui/skia-graphics-engine] Skia is a romanisation of the word 'shadow' in Greek (Σκιά).
[src:avalonia-ui/skia-graphics-engine] Skia Inc, developers of the Skia Graphics Engine, was founded in 2004 by Mike Reed and Cary Clark in Chapel Hill North Carolina, before being acquired by Google in 2005.
